Now suppose that X_ \eta is simple, so that Z is a field. Let \rho \colon Z \to \mathbb {C} be a complex embedding. Then the algebra H_ \rho = H \otimes _{Z, \rho } \mathbb {C} is an algebra of matrices and a bigraded direct factor of H_ \mathbb {C} =H \otimes _ \mathbb {Q} \mathbb {C}. Pick an isomorphism
1574Equationhodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.1hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.1.xml4.4.8.1hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8 H_ \rho \simeq \operatorname {End} (V_ \rho ). \tag{4.4.8.1}
From the fact that the infinitesimal generators of S act on H_ \rho, by derivations, which are necessarily interior, we deduce that V_ \rho admits a bigrading, unique up to translation, such that is a bigraded isomorphism. Let ( \mathrm {R} _1f_* \mathbb {C} )_ \rho be the bigraded local system ( \mathrm {R} _1f_* \mathbb {C} ) \otimes _{Z \otimes \mathbb {C} , \rho } \mathbb {C} which is a direct factor of \mathrm {R} _1f_* \mathbb {C}. Denote by T_ \rho the local system T_ \rho = \operatorname {Hom} _{H_ \rho }(V_ \rho ,( \mathrm {R} _1f_* \mathbb {C} )_ \rho ).

We have the bigraded isomorphism

1575Equationhodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.2hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8.2.xml4.4.8.2hodge-theory-ii-4.4.8         V_ \rho \otimes _ \mathbb {C}  T_ \rho           \xrightarrow { \sim }  ( \mathrm {R} _1f_* \mathbb {C} )_ \rho .       \tag{4.4.8.2}       

Since ( \mathrm {R} _1f_* \mathbb {C} )_ \rho is of degree (-1,0)+(0,-1), one of the following conditions is satisfied:






    V_ \rho is bihomogeneous;





    T_ \rho is bihomogeneous.

The complex conjugation automorphism on
       ( \mathrm {R} _1f_* \mathbb {C} )_ \rho        =(( \mathrm {R} _1f_* \mathbb {Q} ) \otimes _{Z, \varphi } \mathbb {R} ) \otimes _ \mathbb {R} \mathbb {C}      
is "compatible" with  and can be written as
        \sigma        =  \sigma _1 \otimes \sigma _2.     
Since \sigma ^2=1, we have, by , that

1581Equationhodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.2hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.2.xml4.4.9.2hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9          \sigma _1^2         =  \sigma _2^2         =  \varepsilon _{H \rho }.       \tag{4.4.9.2}

Let \psi _ \rho be the form induced on V_ \rho \otimes _ \mathbb {C} T_ \rho. The alternating form \psi _ \rho is invariant under \pi _1(S,s). Since T_ \rho is irreducible, we can write \psi _ \rho as
1582Equationhodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.3hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.3.xml4.4.9.3hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9 \psi _ \rho = A_ \rho \otimes B_ \rho \tag{4.4.9.3}
with A_ \rho on V_ \rho, and B_ \rho on T_ \rho invariant under \pi _1(S,s).

Since T_ \rho is irreducible, B_ \rho is either symmetric or alternating.
Since \psi _ \rho is alternating, A_ \rho is either symmetric or alternating.
Since the T_ \rho are conjugate to one another, whether we are in one case or the other does not depend on \rho.
We set

1583Equationhodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.4hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.4.xml4.4.9.4hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9         A_ \rho (X,Y)         =  \varepsilon _V A_ \rho (Y,X)       \tag{4.4.9.4}       

1584Equationhodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.5hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.5.xml4.4.9.5hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9         B_ \rho (X,Y)         =  \varepsilon _T B_ \rho (Y,X).       \tag{4.4.9.5}       

We thus have

1585Equationhodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.6hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.6.xml4.4.9.6hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9          \varepsilon _V \varepsilon _T         = -1       \tag{4.4.9.6}       

and it is clear by  that if * is the involution of H induced by \psi, then

1586Equationhodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.7hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9.7.xml4.4.9.7hodge-theory-ii-4.4.9          \varepsilon _*         =  \varepsilon _V.       \tag{4.4.9.7}

In case (a) (resp. (b)) of , we normalise the bigradings so that V_ \rho (resp. T_ \rho) is of bidegree (0,0). We then have, for non-zero x \in V_ \rho and non-zero y \in T_ \rho, the two cases:
A_ \rho (x, \sigma _1 x)B_ \rho (y,C \sigma _2 y) >0;
A_ \rho (x,C \sigma _1 x)B_ \rho (y, \sigma _2 y) >0.

By normalising A_ \rho and B_ \rho (of which only their tensor product is given), we can suppose, in each respective case, that






    A_ \rho (x, \sigma _1x)>0 and B_ \rho (y,C \sigma _2y)>0;





    A_ \rho (x,C \sigma _1x)>0 and B_ \rho (y, \sigma _2y).
